âœ… What advantage does TypeScript give us?
TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript that adds static typing and type safety, helping developers catch errors early during development rather than at runtime.

Example:
typescript
Copy
Edit
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}

add(5, 10);     // âœ… works
add("5", "10"); // âŒ Error at compile time
ğŸ”¹ Advantages:
Catches errors before execution

Better code completion & IntelliSense

Easier to maintain large codebases

Supports modern JavaScript features (ES6+)

Helps with documentation via types

âœ… What does TypeScript add to JavaScript?
Static Typing â€“ Variables can have a defined type (number, string, boolean, etc.)

Interfaces & Types â€“ For defining object shapes

Enums â€“ For named constants

Generics â€“ For reusable code with type safety

Access Modifiers (public, private, protected) â€“ For class members

Type Inference â€“ Infers variable type from initial value

Compilation â€“ TS compiles to browser-compatible JS

âœ… Why do we need the TypeScript compiler (tsc)?
The browser cannot run .ts files. The TypeScript compiler (tsc) converts .ts into .js files which browsers understand.

ğŸ”¸ What happens when you compile?
Type checking is done

Errors are reported

Type annotations are removed

.ts is transpiled to .js

âœ… Types available in TypeScript:
Primitive: number, string, boolean, null, undefined

Array: string[], number[]

Tuple

Enum

Any, Unknown, Void, Never

Object

Custom types/interfaces

âœ… Why does add('1', '2') show error when types are defined?
If add is defined as:

ts
Copy
Edit
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}
Calling add("1", "2") gives an error because "1" and "2" are strings, not numbers â€” hence type mismatch.

âœ… What is type inference?
TypeScript can automatically detect the type of a variable:

ts
Copy
Edit
let age = 25; // inferred as number
ğŸ”¸ Advantage:
Less code, cleaner syntax, and still type-safe.

ğŸ”¸ Problem & Solution:
Sometimes inference is incorrect. You can cast it:

ts
Copy
Edit
let input = document.getElementById('username') as HTMLInputElement;
âœ… What does tsc --init do?
It creates a tsconfig.json file that:

Stores compiler options

Enables features like strict mode

Lets you define target JS version (es6, etc.)

âœ… What does strict mode do?
"strict": true in tsconfig.json enables all strict type-checking rules:

No implicit any

Better null checks

Safer code

âœ… What does buttonElement! do? (Non-null assertion)
ts
Copy
Edit
const button = document.getElementById('myBtn')!;
This tells TypeScript:

â€œTrust me, this will not be null.â€
Use carefully â€” if it's actually null, you'll get a runtime error.

âœ… Why shouldnâ€™t we use any type?
any disables type checking â€” defeats the purpose of TypeScript.

You lose auto-complete and safety.

Use unknown or proper types instead.

âœ… How to handle objects in TypeScript?
ts
Copy
Edit
type User = {
  name: string;
  age: number;
};

const user: User = { name: "John", age: 30 };
âœ… Handling Arrays:
